<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-111-167 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 951 862</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  July 1 1991 v25 n26 p68(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IS doors are opening at major hotels. (informationsystems)(includes related article on centralizing hotel industrysystems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>LaPlante, Alice.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Opportunities for information systems (IS) employment at largehotel chains are available.andP;  Many of the industry's major hotelsare upgrading older technologies by developing enterprisewidesystems.andP;  Their ultimate goal is to make hotel operations moreefficient and increase revenue by collecting significantinformation about guests.andP;  A major trend in the hotel industry isthe move away from IBM mainframes to Unix.andP;  Unix iscost-effective, portable and also has sophisticated communicationsfacilities.andP;  IS jobseekers proficient in C, relational databasessuch as Oracle or Informix, or fourth-generation languages thatrun under Unix are particularly valuable to hotel chains.andP;  HotelIS mangers believe the field will be wide open to prospectiveemployees for several years.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Products).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Information systemsEmploymentUNIXMainframe computersManagement of EDPInformation Storage and RetrievalReservation Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>